submodules
https://code.jgi.doe.gov/advanced-analysis/jgi-wdl-catalog



## add new submodule from existing git repository

git submodule add https://gitlab.com/jfroula/jaws-health-test health-test

## clone a repo with one or more submodules
git clone --recurse-submodules https://code.jgi.doe.gov/advanced-analysis/jgi-wdl-catalog.git

## populate existing submodule empty folders into top level repo. You would
## do this if you have just cloned master.  (e.g. git clone <master>.git)

git submodule update --init --recursive


## keep updated submodules.  Do from top level of repo.

git submodule update --remote <submodule name>

(same as git fetch, git merge)


## pushing a main repo with altered submodules
## This goes into each submodule and pushes changes. 
## This is unecessary if you have already gone into each submodule and pushed.

git push --recurse-submodules=on-demand

## Delete submodule

Delete the relevant section from the .gitmodules file.
Stage the .gitmodules changes git add .gitmodules
Delete the relevant section from .git/config.
Run git rm --cached path_to_submodule (no trailing slash).
Run rm -rf .git/modules/path_to_submodule (no trailing slash).
Commit git commit -m "Removed submodule "
Delete the now untracked submodule files rm -rf path_to_submodule
